{{Infobox person | name = Abraham Dirk Loman | image = Prof. A.D. Loman.jpg | alt = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software --> | caption = | birth_name = <!-- only use if different from name --> | birth_date = {{Birth date|1823|9|16}} | birth_place = [[The Hague]] | death_date = {{Death date and age|1897|4|17|1823|9|16}} | death_place = [[Amsterdam]] | nationality = Dutch | other_names = | occupation = Theologian | years_active = | known_for = | notable_works = }}
'''Abraham Dirk Loman''' (16 September 1823, [[The Hague]] – 17 April 1897, [[Amsterdam]]) was a Dutch theologian. He was a professor from 1856 to 1893.<ref>{{cite journal|author=H.U. Meyboom|url=http://www.dbnl.org/tekst/_jaa002189801_01/_jaa002189801_01_0016.php|title=Levensbericht van A.D. Loman |year=1898 |journal=Jaarboek van de Maatschappij der Nederlandse Letterkunde}}</ref> In his later period he belonged to the [[Radical Criticism|Dutch radical critics]].<ref name="Allen">{{cite journal|author=A.J. Allan |url=http://www.radikalkritik.de/A_forgotten_chapter.htm |title=A Forgotten Chapter: the Radicals |journal=Kerk & Wereld |year=1995 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717072449/http://www.radikalkritik.de/A_forgotten_chapter.htm |archivedate=2011-07-17 }}</ref>
==Life== Loman was the son of a [[minister (Christianity)|minister]] in the [[Evangelical Lutheran Church in the Kingdom of the Netherlands|Dutch Lutheran church]]. He started studying theology in 1840 and became a minister in 1846. In 1856 he became a professor at the Lutheran [[seminary]] in Amsterdam. Loman gradually lost his eyesight in the beginning of the 1870s, but continued working. From 1877 he also was a theology professor at the [[University of Amsterdam]] until his retirement in 1893.<ref name="deGroot">{{cite book|author=A. de Groot |chapterurl=http://www.inghist.nl/retroboeken/blnp/#1%3A138 |chapter=Loman, Abraham Dirk |title=Biografisch lexicon voor de geschiedenis van het Nederlands protestantisme |year=1978 }}</ref>
==Work== Loman introduced modern theology in the Dutch Lutheran Church. He taught almost all disciplines of theology, but concentrated after 1867 on the New Testament and early Christian literature. He wrote a book about the [[Muratorian fragment]], but published mostly in journals. His opinions mostly agreed with the [[Tübingen school]]. When his colleague [[Allard Pierson]] in 1878 denied the authenticity of [[Epistle to the Galatians|Galatians]], Loman wrote a fierce condemnation.
But after 1880 his views changed. He was an advocate of the [[Christ myth theory]] and caused great consternation by a public lecture on 13 December 1881 in the [[Paradiso (Amsterdam)|building of the Vrije Gemeente]] where he stated that [[Jesus]] is not a figure of history and that all we know about him is second-century fiction.<ref name="Allen"/> In his ''Quaestiones Paulinae'' (1882, 1883, 1886) he abandoned Pauline authorship of Galatians.<ref name="deGroot"/> His arguments were that the Pauline epistles are not quoted by [[Justin Martyr]] and that the first datable references are by [[Marcion]].<ref name="Schilling">{{cite web|author=Klaus Schilling |year=2003 |url=http://www.radikalkritik.de/vbve_survey.htm |title=A survey: G.A. van den Bergh van Eysinga |publisher=Radikalkritik - de omnibus dubitandum |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717072428/http://www.radikalkritik.de/vbve_survey.htm |archivedate=2011-07-17 }}</ref>
