'''''Kasayapahuda''''' ({{IAST|Kāsāyapahuḍa}}) (also ''Kasayaprabhrta'') is one of the oldest canonical text of the ''[[Digambara]]'' Jains. Another oldest canonical text, the ''[[Shatkhandagama]]'' was written about the same time.<ref name=Hira/> Both these texts are held in high esteem by the ''Digambaras''. ''[[Kashaya (Jainism)|Kasaya]]'' (passions) form the subject matter of ''Kasayapahuda''.

== Author ==

''Kasayapahuda'' was written by ''[[Acharya (Jainism)|Acharya]]'' Gunadhara in the 1st century A.D.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=jp64AAAAIAAJ|p=21|title=Basic mathematics|author1=Jain|first1=Laxmi Chandra|year=1982}}</ref><ref name=Hira/>

== Content ==

''Kasayapahuda'' discusses the Jain doctrine of ''[[Karma in Jainism|Karma]]''.<ref name=Hira>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=uIHXAAAAMAAJ|p=43|title=Jaina Tradition in Indian Thought|isbn=9788185616841|author1=Jaina|first1=Hīrālāla|last2=Jaina|first2=Dharmacandra|date=2002-01-01}}</ref> The ''Kasayapahuda'' is written in verses only.<ref>{{cite book|url= https://books.google.co.in/books?id=ibbWAAAAMAAJ|p=xxvi-xxvii|title=Satkhandāgama: Jīvasthāna|isbn=9788186957479|author1=)|first1=Puṣpadanta (Acharya|last2=Bhūtabali|last3=)|first3=Ashok Kumar Jain (Physicist|year=2004}}</ref>

